        "name": "Kitzbühel",
        "description": "Big names, ski pioneers and the high society &ndash; but also Tyrolean down-to-earthness, Gem&uuml;tlichkeit and hospitality: these contrasts are what make Kitzb&uuml;hel one of the greatest ski resorts in the Alps. Kitzb&uuml;hel is even recognised as the &ldquo;Best Ski Resort in the World&rdquo; for 2013. With 51 cable cars and lifts, connecting 170 kilometres of ski slopes, Bergbahn AG Kitzb&uuml;hel is one of the largest cable car companies in Austria. In addition to the spectacular &ldquo;Streif&rdquo;, Kitzb&uuml;hel trumps with a variety of ski runs suiting all sizes and ski styles. In fact, the vast and snow-reliable ski resort boasts an above-average number of family runs (69 km easy, 77 km intermediate, 24 km difficult). The &ldquo;flagship&rdquo; run is, of course, the Family Streif, which elegantly snakes its way around the extremely steep part of the downhill course, before returning to the original racing track at the Seidlalm, dodging the &ldquo;Hausbergkante&rdquo; ridge on the incline Ganslernhang and ends up back at the usual finish. Don&rsquo;t miss out on the most spectacular lift in the world: the 3S-Umlaufbahn (tri-cable gondola). It spans the 2.5-kilometre wide and 400-meter deep Saukaser Valley between the mountains Pengelstein and the Wurzh&ouml;he. Snowboarders and freeskiers will also find their perfect playground on the Resterh&ouml;he. The experienced QParks team lead by Franz Lechner is responsible for the setup of the Hanglalm Park as well as for the park on the Kitzb&uuml;heler Horn, including all kicker, rail, jib and tree lines, picnic tables and chill-out areas. Skiers and boarders keen to head off-piste will love Kitzb&uuml;hel&rsquo;s 200 km2 backcountry. Around the 32 kilometres of ski routes there are endless opportunities to ride through perfect deep powder snow. After dark, the 700-year-old &ldquo;Old Town&rdquo; with its typical apr&egrave;s ski bars and pubs becomes the social hub of the world. Fashionistas will be in their element hopping between international designer addresses, from Bogner and Boss, Gucci, D&amp;G and Moncler, to Prada and Louis Vuitton. And between them, classic Kitzb&uuml;hel &ldquo;fashion originals&rdquo;, such as Sportalm, Frauenschuh, Franz Prader and Helmut Eder, add a traditional element to the vibrant collection. The &ldquo;town of the chamois&rdquo;, as Kitzb&uuml;hel is affectionately known, is easily accessible by road and by rail. From the airport cities Munich, Salzburg, and Innsbruck, it takes a maximum of one and a half hours by car to get to Kitzb&uuml;hel.",
